AACGCACATTGCGCCTCCTTGTATTCAGGGAGGCATGCCTGTCCGAGCGTCATTAAAAACCACTCAAGCCTGTTGTGCTTGGTCATGGAAGAAGAGTCCGCTTGTCCGGTCTCCTTTCCGAAATACAATGGCGGAAGGTCTCTGGTGCCCGGCGTAGTAATAACTGTTCGCCTTGTGTCTCGAGATGTTTCTGCCGTCAAACCCCCAATTCTTCTTAGGTTGACCTCGGATCAGGTAGGGATACCCGCTGAACTTAA	k__Fungi	p__Ascomycota	c__Pezizomycetes	o__Pezizales	f__Pyronemataceae	g__Tricharina	NA	Genus	Saprotroph	Undefined Saprotroph	Probable	NULL	NULL	"Most if not all of the species in this genus appear to be saprotrophic, although at one point some species were thought to be ectomycorrhizal. The history can be traced back: Rinaldi et al. (2008) cited Agerer (2006), who cited Ingleby et al. (1990), a report that had been based upon a description of ECM formed by Tricharina gilva. The report of Ingleby et al. (1990) was actually based upon a misidentification, as Egger (1996) sequenced dried ascocarp material obtained from Kevin Ingleby and found it to be Wilcoxina mikolae, which is known to form E-strain ECM."	"Egger KN. 1996. Canadian Journal of Botany 74:773-779; Rinaldi AC, Comandini O, Kuyper TW. 2008. Fungal Diversity 33:1-45 (ECM); Tedersoo L, May TW, Smith ME. 2010. Mycorrhiza 20:217-263 (pro parte); http://mycorrhizas.info/ecmf.html (ECM)"
